The paper deals with approximation schemes for geometric optimization problems, which are typically studied in the computational geometry community. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of graphs and their properties, which suggests that it could also be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also presents results on packing and covering problems, which are typically studied in the combinatorial optimization community, suggesting that it could be classified under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
